description:
Purpose: The goal of this 3-year PRO VN partner with IUCN is to develop and implement
field projects as operational pilots for circular economy model
Objective :
• Identify, develop and implement pilot local initiatives of mutual interest and benefits in
plastic waste management, particularly on circular economy project;
• Promote good practices and lesson learn into policy recommendation;
• Provide capacity building support on sustainable business practices; 
Specific area of collaboration: 
These projects can be integrated with on-going projects/initiatives that IUCN has been
implementing:
1. Pilot project/ field activities
• Hoi An City Circular Economy project – scale up from Cham island;
• Plastic pollution: shoreline survey monitoring and assessment (12 sites a long the coast
of Viet Nam with extension to more sites);
2. Policy advocacy/Research/Study
• EPR – Policy Brief and communication and advocacy materials;
• Policy brief on Export and Import of plastic waste issues by advocating for ratification of
the Basel Ban Amendment and improving the national regulations in Law on Environment
Protection revision; Organize the Policy Dialogue at ASEAN Submit and ASEAN People
Forum on Export and Import of plastic waste issues.
• Analysis the capacity of the existing recycle industries;
• Improve quality of recycle plastic materials within Viet Nam;
3. Capacity building
• Plastic Leak Project (PLP)
• Sharing Hotspot analysis

Hoi An is a provincial city in Quang Nam province, central Vietnam. The city consists of nine urban wards and four communes; including the Cham Islands with a total population of 152,160 and a total area of 61.71 km2 (Quang Nam People’s Committee, 2018). Hoi An City is an ancient town, named a National Cultural Heritage Site since 1985 and a UNESCO World Heritage City since 1999. 
	The failure of solid waste classification at sources in Viet Nam in general and in the number of pilot projects funded by both international and domestic sources in Hoi An point out one of the difficulties in the course of implementation: incompatibility between the existent collection and treatment facilities with the processing of separated waste. There is also a lack of funds for collection and disposal infrastructure investment. Failure of waste sorting and appropriate collection as well as treatment are problems in solid waste management. 
The purpose of this pilot project is to test the full cycle steps of the source-to-sea approach by using the practical guidance and methods presented in Implementing the Source-to-Sea Approach: A Guide for Practitioners  and Framework for Marine Litter Prevention: Preventing Plastic Leakage from River Basins  . The pilot in the VG-TB River Basin focused on solid waste flows, in particular plastic leakage to rivers and coastal areas and will cover the all six steps: (1) Characterize; (2) Engage; (3) Diagnose; (4) Design; (5) Act; (6) Adapt;
